Files:
- platform/browser-extension/src/confirmation-badge.ts (remove counter, derive from Map)
- platform/browser-extension/src/confirmation-badge.test.ts (add test for undefined id)

Context:
`pendingConfirmationCount` (line 14) is a separate number that must stay in sync with `pendingConfirmations` Map (line 19). The bug: `clearConfirmationBadge(id?: string)` at line 97 has this flow:
```ts
const clearConfirmationBadge = (id?: string): void => {
  if (id !== undefined) {
    if (!pendingConfirmations.has(id)) {
      return;
    }
    pendingConfirmations.delete(id);
  }
  pendingConfirmationCount = Math.max(0, pendingConfirmationCount - 1);
```
When `id` is undefined, the `if (id !== undefined)` block is skipped entirely, so no map entry is removed, but the counter is still decremented. The caller `handleSpConfirmationResponse` in background-message-handlers.ts (line 358-360) extracts id as:
```ts
const data = message.data as Record<string, unknown> | undefined;
const id = typeof data?.id === 'string' ? data.id : undefined;
```
A malformed confirmation response (data.id not a string) passes undefined.

Changes:
1. Delete `let pendingConfirmationCount = 0;`
2. In `updateConfirmationBadge`, replace `pendingConfirmationCount > 0` with `pendingConfirmations.size > 0` and `String(pendingConfirmationCount)` with `String(pendingConfirmations.size)`
3. In `syncConfirmationNotification`, replace `pendingConfirmationCount <= 0` with `pendingConfirmations.size === 0`, and `pendingConfirmationCount > 1` / `pendingConfirmationCount === 1` with `pendingConfirmations.size > 1` / `pendingConfirmations.size === 1`. Also update the message template: `${pendingConfirmationCount} tools` â†’ `${pendingConfirmations.size} tools`
4. In `notifyConfirmationRequest`, remove `pendingConfirmationCount++`
5. In `clearConfirmationBadge`, remove `pendingConfirmationCount = Math.max(0, pendingConfirmationCount - 1)`. Also: when `id` is undefined, the function should be a no-op (return early) since there's nothing to clear without an id.
6. In `clearAllConfirmationBadges`, remove `pendingConfirmationCount = 0`

Constraints:
- Do NOT change the function signatures â€” `clearConfirmationBadge(id?: string)` must still accept an optional id
- Do NOT change the Map key type or the PendingConfirmationParams interface
- `getPendingConfirmations()` return value must not change shape

Files:
- platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/components/PluginCard.tsx (fix rollback mechanism)

Context:
The current code uses shared refs for rollback state:
```ts
const preToggleRef = useRef<WireToolDef[]>([]);
const prePluginPermRef = useRef<ToolPermission>('off');
const toggleCounter = useRef(0);
```

For tool permissions, `applyToolPermission` (line 114-126):
```ts
const applyToolPermission = (toolName: string, newPermission: ToolPermission) => {
  const myVersion = ++toggleCounter.current;
  updatePluginTools(prev => {
    preToggleRef.current = prev;
    return prev.map(t => (t.name === toolName ? { ...t, permission: newPermission } : t));
  });
  void setToolPermission(plugin.name, toolName, newPermission).catch(() => {
    if (toggleCounter.current === myVersion) {
      updatePluginTools(() => preToggleRef.current);
    }
    showToggleError(`Failed to update ${toolName}`);
  });
};
```

The race: if two rapid tool changes fire, the second overwrites `preToggleRef.current` with the array that already includes the first's optimistic update. If only the first fails, its rollback is skipped (counter check). But if the second then fails, it rolls back to pre-second state (which includes first's optimistic update that the server rejected).

The same pattern exists for `prePluginPermRef` in `applyPluginPermission` (line 73-91).

Changes:
Replace the shared refs with per-operation rollback tracking. The simplest approach:

1. For tool permissions: Instead of storing the entire tools array, store only the previous permission value of the specific tool being changed. Use a Map<number, { toolName: string; previousPermission: ToolPermission }> keyed by the toggle counter version.

Example approach:
```ts
const pendingToolRollbacks = useRef<Map<number, { toolName: string; prev: ToolPermission }>>(new Map());

const applyToolPermission = (toolName: string, newPermission: ToolPermission) => {
  const myVersion = ++toggleCounter.current;
  const currentPerm = pluginTools.find(t => t.name === toolName)?.permission ?? 'off';
  pendingToolRollbacks.current.set(myVersion, { toolName, prev: currentPerm });
  updatePluginTools(prev => prev.map(t => (t.name === toolName ? { ...t, permission: newPermission } : t)));
  void setToolPermission(plugin.name, toolName, newPermission).catch(() => {
    const rollback = pendingToolRollbacks.current.get(myVersion);
    if (rollback) {
      updatePluginTools(prev => prev.map(t => (t.name === rollback.toolName ? { ...t, permission: rollback.prev } : t)));
    }
    showToggleError(`Failed to update ${toolName}`);
  }).finally(() => {
    pendingToolRollbacks.current.delete(myVersion);
  });
};
```

2. For plugin permissions: Same pattern â€” store the previous permission per operation.
```ts
const pendingPluginRollbacks = useRef<Map<number, ToolPermission>>(new Map());
```

Constraints:
- Do NOT change the optimistic update behavior â€” UI must still update immediately on click
- Do NOT change the public API (handlePluginPermissionChange, handleToolPermissionChange signatures)
- The unreviewed plugin dialog flow (pendingChange state) must continue to work
- Remove preToggleRef and prePluginPermRef entirely â€” do not leave dead code

Files:
- platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/hooks/useServerNotifications.ts (extend handler)

Context:
The tab.stateChanged handler at line 65-76:
```ts
if (data.method === 'tab.stateChanged' && data.params) {
  const params = data.params as Record<string, unknown>;
  if (
    typeof params.plugin === 'string' &&
    typeof params.state === 'string' &&
    validTabStates.has(params.state) &&
    VALID_PLUGIN_NAME.test(params.plugin)
  ) {
    const pluginName = params.plugin;
    const newState = params.state as TabState;
    setPlugins(prev => prev.map(p => (p.name === pluginName ? { ...p, tabState: newState } : p)));
  }
}
```

The notification params contain a `tabs` array (type `PluginTabInfo[]` with fields `tabId`, `url`, `title`, `ready`) that is being ignored. The side panel uses `plugin.tabs?.length` for the tab count tooltip in PluginCard.tsx (line 148: `const tabCount = plugin.tabs?.length ?? 0`).

The `tabs` array is sent by `sendTabStateNotification` in messaging.ts:
```ts
const params = {
  plugin: pluginName,
  state: stateInfo.state,
  tabs: stateInfo.tabs,
};
```

Changes:
In the handler, extract and validate the tabs array, then include it in the state update:
```ts
const pluginName = params.plugin;
const newState = params.state as TabState;
const newTabs = Array.isArray(params.tabs) ? params.tabs as PluginTabInfo[] : undefined;
setPlugins(prev => prev.map(p => (
  p.name === pluginName
    ? { ...p, tabState: newState, ...(newTabs !== undefined ? { tabs: newTabs.length > 0 ? newTabs : undefined } : {}) }
    : p
)));
```

Note: import `PluginTabInfo` from `@opentabs-dev/shared`. This is a type-only import so it won't cause CSP issues in the side panel bundle.

Constraints:
- Do NOT validate individual tab entries â€” trust the background script's data
- When tabs is absent (backwards compat), do not clear the existing tabs array â€” only tabState is updated
- When tabs is an empty array, set tabs to undefined (matches the convention in bg:getFullState where empty tabs are omitted)
